## What I learned
- Pointers -> & means get the address (what is the address???)
			  * means it goes to that address (go to that address!!!)
- * is also called dereferencing

	For ex: int n = 50;
		int *p = &n;
		
		printf("%i", *p); -> 50
- Memory management: 
	1. SMA - Static memory allocation: all declared variables (uninitialized local variables and initialized variables). Will be present at compile time. Goes to stack.
	2. DMA - Dynamic memory allocation: variables declared during run time (uses malloc, calloc, realloc and free). Goes to Heap.
	3. Data segment - global declared variables
	4. bss - undeclared global variables
- Don't forget to use free() or it will do memory leak: It means that when you initialize a variable using malloc (for ex. p), the initialized variable is in stack. But it points to the dynamically allocated variable in heap. If you don't use heap, stack will destroy the value p but the memory in heap is still there and cannot be consumed so it gets wasted. 
- Use %p for addresses.
- sizeof operator is of type size_t which is unsigned. Use %zu to get value.
- (1 << 7) - directly means that I am moving 1 to 7th bit and reast all are 0 (bits 0-6).

